Potential causes include low‑quality bases in the DADA2 denoising step leading to erroneous ASVs; amplification of non‑target DNA such as host genes or PhiX; limitations of the reference database or classifier settings. To mitigate, you can:
- filter out features or sequences that carry the taxonomy label “Unassigned” or “Bacteria;__”;
- filter out sequences that do not align well to a 16S reference (BLAST against the mouse genome or PhiX to identify contaminants);
- use Deblur (forward reads only) which applies an 85% identity filter against the Greengenes reference, often removing host variants;
- use QIIME 2’s quality‑control exclude‑seqs with vsearch against a 99% reference database (e.g., 99_otus) to generate a hits and misses table, then filter the feature table and rep‑seqs to remove misses.
These steps have been reported to resolve the high proportion of unassigned or kingdom‑level assignments.
